const errorData = [{"Error message": "Best focus errors occurrung mid-run on the MSQ", "Solution": "Either library, instrument, or run set-up can lead to a mid-run (after cycle 1) best focus error.\n\nPossible library and reagent cause are:\n(1. Use of expired or improperly stored reagents\n(2. Library design and/ or quality/ qualification issues\n(3. Use of incompatable primers if custom primers are used for later reads\n(4. Under-or overclustering\nPossible instrumentation causes include:\n(1. Poor delivery of reagents involved in cluster generation or first base chemistry\n(2. Flow cell temperature control issues\n(3. Optical system issues\nPossible Run Set-Up causes include:\n(1. Setting up run with total number of cycles greater than what is supportes be the kit\n(2. Selecting a Custom Primer in the run setup when one is not intended\n\nTroubleshooting step:\n1. Review run data to confirm run performance. If library issue is not suspected, troubleshoot instrument.\n* Verify total cycles called for in run length is compatible with the reagent ki used\n* Check reagent kits for expiration dates and proper storage\n* Make sure the library design is compatable to run on OriginFactor platforms.\n* Check the quality and qualification of the library using OriginFactor-recommend methods\n* Make sure custom primers are compatable with the 65℃ annealing temperature for the MSQ\n* Make sure custom primers are added to the correct cartridge wells (spiked into existing primer wells with no change to the samole sheet, or add to custom primer wells  wiht the sample sheet indicating that custom primers are being used)\n2. To ensure that the instrument's fluidics, temperature and motion system are performing as expected, first perform a SYS_Chk by Egr on the instrument.\n3. If SYS_Chk passes, set up next run", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image1.png"}, {"Error message": "Black Screen at boot up: How to access Windows if there is Black Screen at boot up on MSQ", "Solution": "1. CTRL + ALT +DEL\n2. End process \"MSQSoftware.exe\"", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/iamge6.png"}, {"Error message": "Blue Screen of Death, Black Screen or Monitor off on the MSQ", "Solution": "Ask customer:\n(1. Have there been any power issue at the site\n(2. Is the MSQ instrument plugged in through a  universal power supply (UPS)\n(3. Are there other MSQ instruments running in the lab with the same configuration?\n(4. Is the power switch still on?\n\nCheck:\n1. Ensure user has full admin privileges\n2. Check logs for time of error\n3. Check Asset case historyfor past occurrences\n4. Check programs and features:\n* C_SW 2.5 should have .NET 4.0\n* C_SW 2.6 should have .NET 4.5\n* C_SW 3.1 should have .NET 4.5.1\n\n5. Check control panel - system and security -windows update - view update historey --> checl ddor updates at time of reboot\n6. Check control panel - Action Center - change action center setting - uncheck setting like Windows Update, etc\n7. Check event logs to ensure system was power cycled. Check System, Application. and Security Event logs for errors.\n8. Check Applications Log for Anti-Virus software scanning during sequencing run\n9. Check crash dumo files:\n* Create crash dump - Task Manager - Applicaiton - right click on C_SW\n* Open program winbdg - to open file (file location C:\\User\\sbsuser\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\MSQSoftware.DMP)\n* Command: !analyze -v\n10. Check RTA error logs\n11. Check Windows Task Manager - Performance tab screenshot to ensure that system has RAM 16Gb\n12. Ensure customer is complying with Antivirus Software configuraion\n13. Run GPO report and send to Second Level Support\n* Open command prompt \"CMD\" and enter\n* Enter the followong command at the prompt (including quotes): gpresukt/r /v >\"C:\\users\\sbsuser\\desktop\\GPO result.txt\n\nIf troubleshooting does not result in a clear root cause, and this is the first occurrence of issue, power cycle and set up next run. Monitor instrument.\n\nIf error occurs again, assign work order to Egr to replace hard disk drive (HDD)\n\nIf issue reoccurs after HDD replcaement, single-board computer (SBC) should be replaced by Egr.\n\nNOTE: If case is elevated, replcae HDD and SBC. Run instrument off the network for next 2 runs, if possible.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Bottom surface Q30 drops at read number greater then first read on MSQ", "Solution": "The Q30 drops because the Bottom surface coarse Through-focus step selects the wrong surface (Top), always occurs after read 1.\n\nBest-Z differences can be causes by variation in run flow cells and SFBFC or incorrect MSQOverride.cfg entries (coarsefocuscenterz, throughfocuscenterz, tiltuntilfocuscenterz) or shifting optical components.\n\n1. Review SAV Q30 plot for run to verify only bottom surface is impacted.\n2. Cycle logs, example thumbnail images for impacted cycles, MSQOverride.cfg, and Effective.cfg files.\n3. Confirm issue with Second Level Support\n4. Assign work order to Egr", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/iamge7.png"}, {"Error message": "Bubble in MSQ flow cell", "Solution": "No troubleshooting required\nFlow cell can be used to start run.\nAdvies customer to use flow cell as bubble will be pushed through when fluidics engage during pre-run check.\nRun performance is not typically impacted", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Cavro Pump Error on MSQ", "Solution": "Cavro Pump error can result from problems with the hardware or communicaiton errors.\n\n1. Power cycle\n2. If no issues with re-initialization, perform pst-run wash to ensure fluidics opreating normally.\n* Can opotionally pereform a volume test withi the SYS_Chk\n* If there is a hardware related component fialing, C_SW may fail to initialze, or will not complete the wash successfully\n3. If error persists, assign work order to Egr. The syringe pump (PN 15025370S) and cable (PN150020034S) may need to be checked or replaced", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image8.png"}, {"Error message": "Chemistry Step error just before starting a run on MSQ", "Solution": "This error occurs at the beginning of the run (no reagents are taken from the cartridge) and can be related to an issue with the Sample Sheet.\n\nIt is likely that before this notification error, customer encountered an issue during the run set-up with the error 'an error has occured while reading the reipe fragments'\n\nChemistry step ' firstReadPreparation' is invalid: Error in PumpToFlowCell Node. Could not find either a reagent name or a solution.\n\nTrounleshooting step:\n(1. Check Sample Sheet for:\n(2. Illegal characters in both in the name of the file and in the file itself.\n(3. Appropriate number of cycles for the used cartridge\n(4. Check for the required information the Sample Sheet.\n\nActions:\nCreate a new sample sheet\n\nNOTE: Sample sheet mat be corrupt. Using current sample sheet is not recommended.\n1. Power cycle\n2. Restart the run", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Cycle 1 Errors on the MSQ", "Solution": "Either library, setup, instrument or reagent issues can lead to a Cycle 1 failure on MSQ\n* Potential errors include:\n* Best focus not found\n* Best focus is too near the edge of range\n* No usable signal found, it is possible clustering has failed\n* Through-focus peak did not exceed SNR threshold\n* Z Motor attempt to move outside soft limits\n* New in MCD 4.0 : ThroughFocusScan CoarseFocus failed to find focus, and there is no fallback position\n\nErrors that occur after the first cycle of imaging on the MSQ indicate there may be insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus. If a focus error occurs later in the run ( such as in the first cycle of the index read ) please see No intensity dor index read\n\nPossible instrument causes include:\n(1. Poor delivery of reagents involve in cluster generation or first base chemistry\n(2. Flow cell temperature control issue,\n(3. Optical system issues ( rarely)\n\nPossible library and reagent cause are:\n(1. Use of expired or improperly stored reagent\n(2. Contamination of wash tray\n(3. Library design and/ or qualitification issues\n(4. Poor Read 1 primer hybridization due to library design issue\n(5. Use of incompatible primers\n(6. Under-or overclustering\n(7. NaOH ph issue\n\n1. To ensure that the instrument;s fluidicsm temperature and motion systems are performing as expected, first perform a SYS_Chk, if SYS_Chk passes, the failure may be due to an issue with the library or reagents.\n* check reagent kits for expiration dates and proper storage\n* Make sure the library design is compatible to run on OriginFactor platforms\n* Check the qualit and qualitificatioin of the library using OriginFactor-recommended methods\n* Make sure custom primers are compatible with the 65℃ annealing temperature for the MSQ\n* Make sure custom primers are added to the correct cartridge wells (spiked into existing primer wells with no change to the sample sheet, or added to custom primer wells with the sample sheet indicating thar custom primers are being used)\n* Ask the customer if they prepared a fresh dilution of NaOH and ensure that the pH is above 12.5\n2. If there are no appear issues with the library or reagents, repeat the run with a 20% PhiX control spike in.\n3. If an additional No Usable Signal or Best Focus error occur at cycle 1 of the next runm assign work order to Egr", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image9.png"}, {"Error message": "Failed to Read Temperature Error on the MSQ", "Solution": "Theis error indicates that the MSQ was unable to read the temperature of the flow cell \n\n1. No action required if run does not stop\n2. Power cycle after current run completes", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image10.png"}, {"Error message": "Focus Mirror Error on the MSQ", "Solution": "This error usually mentions the M3 or focus mirror.\n\nError Message: FocusMirror:Focus mirror move and/ or sensor failed: The FPGA reported an error while executing command \"FOCMRRFOC\" error message: \"Focus Mirror sensor not found.\"\n\nTroubleshooting Steps:\n1. Power cycle MSQ. Note that if a run is in progress, it will not be able to be resumed\n2. If system initializes, run the M3 Mirror Test in the SYS_Chk 5 times to verify mirror moving correctly. If any of the tests fail, task Egr.\n* If all 5 tests of M3 mirror pass, continue with next run.\n3. If the system does not initialize Egr\n\nParts Order\n(1. If error occured during run, replace kit under instrument warranty if applicable\n(2. If error occured prior to run start, request customer to return flow cell to storage and discard reagent cartridge. Replace reagent cartridge under instrument warranty if applicable", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image11.png"}, {"Error message": "Unable to measure Flow Rate Errors on the MSQ", "Solution": "Error occurs when the MSQ cannot complete a flow check, or measure the flow rate during the flow check. This is often caused by the flow cell not being aligned with the flow cell manifold. It can also be caused by blockages in the flow cell or reagent lines, orby communicaitons issues in the instrument.\n\n1. Inspect the flow cell and gasket for any signs of damage\n* If the gasket is raised or distorted, do not use\n* If the gasket is flush, clean and reseat the flow cell\n2. Clean and reseat the flow cell\n*Lightly rinse the flow cell with laboratory-grade water until both the glass and plastic cartridge are throughly rinsed of excess salts.\n* Clean the flow cell glass with an alcohol wipe, but do not use alcohol on the gasket\n3. If the flow check still fails, power cycle the instrument\n* Turn off for at least 2 minutes\n* Perform another flow check\n4. If the flow cell still fails, use a different flow cell\n* Continue with the run setup and perform another flow check\n* If the flow check passes, record the lot number of the flow cell and email TS team\n5. If new flow cell fails, task the Egr to inspect the manifold. It is possible there is a hardware related root  cause resulting in failure rto measure flow rate\n* If second flow cell works, collect the lot and serial numer for the original flow cell and replace under the consumable warranty.", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "<img src=\"images/image12.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image13.png>"}, {"Error message": "FPGA RFID ERROR STATUS 2 errors on the MSQ", "Solution": "The FPGA mediate communication between subsystems of the MSQ. If communicaiton is lost with a subsystem, C_SW will show an error message.\n\n1. Verify run completed successfully\n2. Post run wash\n3. Power cycle\n4. If error persists, task Egr\n5. If instrument initializes without error, advise customer to set up next run", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image14.png"}, {"Error message": "FPGA Timeout Errors on the MSQ", "Solution": "The FPGA mediate communication between subsystems of the MSQ. If it lose communication with a subsystem, C_SW will show a software message mentioning the FPGA timeout.\n\nWRN: FPGA: FPGA: Expected no response from FPGA: command = EXLED1ON; Response = ?\n\nERR: Timeout of 60.000 senconds exceeded while waiting for FPGA command\n\nWRN: Y Motor: UpdatePositionAndLimits failed: FPGA: unable to write 'YRDPOS\\n': Exception = 'The write timed out.'\nWRN: Y Motor: Y Motor: MoveAbsScaled failed: Y Motor: UpdatePositoinAndLimits failed: FPGA: Unable to write 'YRDPOS\\n' Exception = 'The write timed out.'\n\n1. Post run wash\n2. Power cycle\n3. If error persists, task Egr\n4. If instrument initailizes without error, advise customer to set up next run.\n\n* Persistent FPGA errors usually point to electronics issues or defective parts. If a power cycle doesn't clear  it, a service visit will be necessary.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "High Cluster Density on MSQ", "Solution": "Best practices for quantification:\nAccurate quantification and proper quality check of next-generation sequencing libraries is key to a\nsuccessful sequencing run.\nDifferent methods for quantification and quality control are recommended depending on the sequencing\nlibrary kit being used. For more information: Library quantification and quality control quick reference\nguide187.\nConsider the average size of your library. Because the clustering process preferentially amplifies shorter\nlibraries in a mixture of fragments, large libraries tend to cluster less efficiently than smaller libraries. For\nmore information: Nextera Library Validation and Cluster Density Optimization188.\nBest practices for denaturation and dilution:\nThe 2N NaOH stock solution must have a pH >12.5 prior to any dilution. Check the pH of the stock solution\nbefore diluting.\nAlways prepare freshly diluted NaOH for denaturing libraries for cluster generation. Use within 12 hours of\npreparation, if not sooner. This step is essential to the denaturation process.\nTo prevent small pipetting errors from affecting the final NaOH concentration, prepare at least 1 ml of\nfreshly diluted NaOH.\nIf your library requires a final concentration > 20 pM, make sure that the NaOH concentration is ≤ 0.05 N in\nthe denaturation solution and ≤ 0.001 N (1 mM) in the final solution diluted with HT1. Higher concentrations\ninhibit hybridization and decrease cluster density.\nFor highly structured or GC-rich libraries, cluster density consistency improves when the library is heat\ndenatured before loading the sample onto the instrument. This method is optional for other libraries.\nAfter NaOH denaturation of the sequencing library and dilution in HT1 to the final loading\nconcentration, incubate the diluted library at 96°C for 2 minutes using a heat block.\nAfter the heat incubation, invert the tube 1–2 times to mix.\nQuickly move the library to an ice water bath for 5 minutes. The quick cooling step helps lock the\nlibrary in its single stranded form.\nProceed immediately to cluster generation.\nBest practices for sequencing low diversity libraries:\nNucleotide diversity is required for effective template generation on OriginFactor sequencing platforms and is\nimportant for the generation of high-quality data.\nDiversity is especially important during the first 4–7 cycles of the first sequencing read for MSQ systems.\nThe sequencing software uses images from these early cycles to identify the location of each cluster in a\nprocess called template generation.\nThe newest versions of Real-Time Analysis (RTA) software optimize the estimation of the color normalization\nmatrix calculations and phasing/pre-phasing rates. These enhancements allow for low diversity and\nunbalanced libraries to be sequenced with a lower percentage of balanced library spike-in for color balance,\nresulting in higher quality sequencing data.\nA minimum of 5% PhiX is required for sequencing low base diversity libraries on MSQ. The PhiX Control v3\nLibrary has a diverse base composition (45% GC and 55% AT) that provides the balanced fluorescent signals that low diversity sample libraries lack during each sequencing cycle. This, in turn, assists with template\nregistration and improves overall run quality.\nReduce the library loading concentration to target a cluster density 30–40% beneath the optimal range for\nthe chemistry version and platform used. The optimal amount of reduction required must be empirically\ndetermined.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Improper recipe format/ recipe fragments error during run set-up on MSQ", "Solution": "The Improper Recipe Format error occurs during run set-up in the review stage and can be related to an issue with\nthe Sample Sheet.\nError details:\nImproper recipe format. An error has occured while reading in the recipe fragments. Please correct it and retry.\nPress ‘Back’ to select a different sample sheet or run.\nTroubleshooting steps:\n-Check Sample Sheet:\nillegal character both in the name of the file and on the file itself\nAppropriate number of cycles for the used cartridge\n-Check for the essential information required in the Sample Sheet\nActions:\nCreate a new sample sheet.\nNOTE: It is possible the file is corrupt, so using the current sample sheet is not recommended.\nFollow How to Shut down or power cycle the MSQ193 to power cycle.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Index outside the bounds of the array error on the MSQ", "Solution": "This error can result from several different factors, but generally terminates the run and requires a re-run fo the sample with a new kit.\n\nPossible causes:\n* Over-clustering or under-clustering\n* Samplesheet issue\n* Potential software error\n* Issue with flowcell preventing focus\n* Potential HDD issue\n\n1. Check library loading concentration\n2. Check Windows logs for indications of software issues\n3. Check if D drive is full, clear space\n4. Power cycle, task Egr perform SYS_Chk and repeat run", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Low Density on MSQ", "Solution": "For a MSQ running v2 reagents, expected cluster density for well-balanced libraries is 1000-1200K/mm2; MSQ running v3 reagents is 1200-1400K/mm2\n\nCommon causes of low cluster density include:\n* Inaccurate quatification of the library \n* Unsuccessful library denaturation with sodium hydroxide\n* Reagent catridge storage or handling \n* A variety of instrument issues\n\nLibrary Qualification \nLibrary quantification is critical to optimizing data output and quality. The MSQ supports loading concentrations\nof 6-10 pM for v2 and 6-20 pM for v3 reagent kits. Accurate quantification of libraries is essential to optimize the\nloading concentration.\nqPCR is the most sensitive and accurate library quantification method, but requires a standard library of\nknown concentration that has similar composition to the libraries to be sequenced. qPCR also requires\nadditional equipment and reagents. PhiX is not recommended for use as the standard. qPCR has the\nadvantage of only quantifying library molecules with adapters on both ends that can form a cluster.\nFluorescent dye quantification such as the Qubit assay can be accurate, if performed correctly. Fresh\nstandards should be made daily, and pipettes should be calibrated regularly. Dye quantification will not\nmeasure single-stranded DNA, but will include library molecules that have damaged ends and will not form\nclusters.\nThe Bioanalyzer can measure concentration, but the measurement is often accurate only to a factor of two.\nBioanalyzer measurements can be confirmed by more sensitive techniques.\nSpectrophotometric quantification, such as Nanodrop, does not give accurate enough concentrations to be\nuseful for quantification of libraries.\nSequencing libraries should be stored in the freezer in low-bind tubes.\nNaOH Acidified\nIt’s important to use NaOH at the right concentration when denaturing libraries. If the NaOH is not at the correct\nconcentration, it will have a lower pH and not denature the library into single strands. Double-stranded libraries\nwill not anneal to the flow cell and will fail to form clusters.\nNaOH should be made to 0.2 N, giving a pH of 12.5. It should be made fresh regularly, as it will acidify quickly in\natmosphere at this concentration.\nNaOH solutions can be pH tested with a pH meter or pH strips for alkaline solutions. If the pH of a 0.2 N NaOH\nsolution is below 12.5, the NaOH will not be able to denature libraries efficiently enough to maximize cluster\ndensity.\nIt's also possible to have too much NaOH in a denaturation reaction. This can occur when loading high\nconcentrations of library that are not diluted sufficiently.\n\n1. Check expiration date\n2. task Egr, check Chiller temperature\n3. SYS_Chk", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Lane Pump Errors on the MSQ", "Solution": "Erro in LanePump. Syringe pump valve failed to move: Valve overload. Command = '/1Q\\r', reply = 'j'\n\nThese errors can occure if the pump that pulls reagents through the MSQ does not response to commands.\n\n1. Power cycle\n2. If no issues with reinitialization, run maintenance wash\n3. If the issue is persists, the syringe pump may need to be replaced. Assign work order to Egr who will check/ replace the syringe pump and cable (part no. 20025890 (including bracket, syringe, and cable))", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image17.png"}, {"Error message": "C_SW Frozen on MSQ", "Solution": "C_SW may freeze if the instrument has not been power cycled for an extended period of time. Freezing can occure idle and a maintenance wash.\n\n1. Power cycle \n2. If software does not close by selecting X in the upper right corner, select CTRL+ALT+DEL to open Task Manager, Right-click C_SW and End Process\n3. If software still does not c;ose, a hard reboot may need to performed by turning of the power switch on the back of the instrument.\n* This is the least describle optioin and should only be used if softwarewill not close using the previously described methods.\n* If issues with initialization occur after a hard reboot, a full power cycle may be required.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Mid Run Shutdown or Reboot on the MSQ", "Solution": "Mid Run Instrument Shutdown can result from enviromental or instrument related root causes.\n\nTo Troubleshoot  an Environmental at Power Supply:\n1. Verify no interruption to power cycle outage was sustained duing the shutdown (Note: Customer amy need to speak with their facilities team to verify)\n2. Verify instrument is connected to UPS\n3. Check if other equipment/ instruments in lab were impacted\n4. If this has occurred in the past, check to see if there is a commonality in time/ frequency\n\nTo Troubleshoot instrument Related Root cause (cycle logs, C_SW logs, windows event logs)\n1. Review last cycle of run cycle logs in D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Temp\\<Run_Folder>\\Logs. If run has exited for non-C_SW related reason last entry in final cycle written will appear incomplete/ interrupted. Note the date/ time for last entry.\n* If the instrument shutdown mid run, we would not expect an error to be recorded in the cycle logs\n2. If \"exiting\" run entry is found, search in log above to locate hardware reason have exited.\nReview C_SW logs at time of unexpected shutdown\n1. Verify C_SW has not logged a planned closure\n2. Scan log for same time as last cycle entry above\nReview Windows event logs\n1. Scan the applicaitons, system, and security windows event logs for andy events coinciding with time of instrument shutdown\n* Application log: any recently installed applications\n2. Security log: any recently updated antivirus software, or antivirus scans\n3. System log: windows system related root causes. Example: shutdown related windows event IDs\nCheck Installed products for newly installed porducts\n1. View Installed Products: Control Panel > Programs and Features > Uninstall or Change a Progam > Sort by installed on date to view if any recently installed programs are present\nChcek Windows updates for recently applied windows updates\n1. Windows 10: Start Menu > Setting > update and Security > Windows Update > Update History > open to view if any recently installed updates", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "No Intensity for index read on MSQ", "Solution": "If the index read has no intensity for the entire read, or if C_SW (C_SW) gives a focus error at the\nfirst cycle of the index read, the library and the index sequencing primer may be incompatible. If the index\nsequencing primer cannot bind to the library, no intensity will be generated during SBS chemistry. If there is some\nintensity during the index read, there may be issues with other steps of the index preparation chemistry.\n\nTroubleshooting steps:\n1. Sample not indexed Many sequencing libraries do not contain an index read. If there is no index in the adapters used to construct a sequencing library, there will be no intensity for the index read. Libraries built with the older Genomic DNA Sample Preparation Kit, Paired-End DNA Sample Preparation Kit, or mRNA-Seq Sample Preparation Kit will have no index. OriginFactor PhiX libraries have no index. All TruSeq library preparation kits build libraries with an index. If there is no intensity for the index read, software errors, loss of focus, or poor quality basecalls may\noccur even if sequencing of the library is successful. In most cases, the run will continue through the index read and the results of the index read can be ignored.\n2. Custom sample prep\nLibraries constructed with nonstandard preparation protocols may not give sufficient intensity for high-quality sequencing. Nonstandard library preparation protocols often require optimization for success with OriginFactor sequencers. Use of custom sequencing primers typically requires optimization on each instrument.\n3. Custom sequencing primers\nSome custom libraries require custom sequencing primers. If a custom sample preparation typically works on the MSQ but does not form clusters for a specific run, the required custom sequencing primers may not have been added, or may not have been specified in the sample sheet.\n4. Delivery issues during index chemistry\nThe isntrument may have failed to properly deliver the index sequencing primer. Run SYS_Chk for volumer to verify primer delivery", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "No Usable Signal Found, It is Possible Clustering Has Failed at Cycle 1 Error", "Solution": "The following errors may occur after the first cycle of imaging on the MSQ and indicate insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus. This can be due to too high of cluster density, too low of cluster density, or a complete failure to cluster.\n* Best focus ont found \n* Best focus is too near the edge of range\n* No usable signal found, it is possible clustering has failed\n* Through-foucs peak did ont exceed SNR threshold\n* Z Motor attempt to move outside soft limits\n* New in C_SW (C_SW) v4.0: ThroughFocusScan CoarseFocus failed to find focus, and there is no fallback position\n\nCycle 1 errors can result from library,  run step, instrument, and reagent issues\n\nCycle 1 errors indicate the instrument was unable to identify sufficient siganl  at cycle 1 and could not compatible the approriate focal point on the flow cell. Errors that occur after the first  cycle of imaging on the MSQ indicate there may be insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus.\n\nIf a focus error occurs later in the run (Such as in the first cycle of the index read or in the niddle of Read 1 or Read 4)  for futher information, search for Knowledge Base article(s): Troubleshooting best focus errors occuring mid-run on the MSQ, Troubleshooting Z motor erros occuring mid- run, and Troubleshooting No intensity for Index Read on MSQ.\n\nPossible instrument causes include:\n* Poor delivery of reagents involve in cluster generation or first base chemistry.\n* Flow cell temperature control issues.\n* Optical systems issues (rare)\n\nPossible library and reagent cause are:\n* Use of expired or improperly stored reagents\n* Library design and/ or quality/ quantificaiton issues.\n* Poor Read 1 primer hybridization due to library design issues\n* Use of incompatible preimers\n* Underclustered or overclustered libraries.\n* NaOH pH issue \n* Contamination of wassh tray\n\nTroubleshooting Steps:\nTo verify the instrument fluidics, temperature, and motion systems are performing as expected, first perform a SYS_Chk on the instrument as described in the MSQ System Guide:\n1. Perform the post run wash as prompted by the instument.\n2. Power cycle the instrument as described in the System Guide.\n3. Navigate to Manager instrument, then select SYS_Chk.\n4. Select all motion tests, primer reagent lines, and both thermal ramping and volume tests\n\nIf the SYS_Chk passes, the failure may be due to an issue with the library or reagents. To investigate the most common issues:\n1. Check reagent kits for expiration dates and proper storage.\n2. Make sure the library design is compatible to run on OriginFactor platforms.\n3. Chcek the quality and quantification of the library using OriginFactor-recommended methods.\n4. Make sure custom primers are compatible with the MSQ.\n5. Make sure cusotm primers are added to the correct cartridge wells (spiked into existing primer wells with no change to the smaple sheet, or added to custom primer wells with the sample sheet indicating that custom primers are being used).\n6. Confirm that a fresh dilution of NaOH was used and the pH is above 12.5.\n\nIf there are no apparent issues with library or reagents, repeat the run with a 20% PhiX control spike in. This will act as a positive control for clustring for the next run to determine  if the previous error was caused by an underlying library issue.", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image1.png"}, {"Error message": "PR2 Bottle Not Detected Error on the MSQ", "Solution": "This error can occur if the PR2 buffer bottle is not recognized be the MSQ\n\n1. Reseat PR2\n* Open the reagent compartment door and raise the sipper handle\n* Remove the PR2 buffer bottle\n* Set it back into place, making sure it sits straight\n* Lower the sipper handle, making sure the sipper goes into the PR2 bottle\n* Close the reagent compartment door\n2. If step 1 does not resolve issue, turn PR2 bottle\n* Open the reagent compartment door and raise the sipper handle\n* Remove the PR2 buffer bottle and turn it 180 degrees (back to front)\n* Set it back into place, making sure it sits straight \n* Lower the sipper handle, making sure thee sipper goes into the PR2 bottle\n* Close the reagent compartment door.\n3. If step 2 does not resolve issue, move sipper handle\n* With the C_SW software showing the PR2 bottle not able to be read, open the reagent compartment\n* Firmly push the sipper handle toward the back of the instrument\n4. If step 3 does not resolve issue, power cycle instrument \n5. If step 4 does not resolve issue, try new PR2 bottle", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Reagent Valve Error on the MSQ", "Solution": "This error can include the phrase \"ReagentValve ReadResponse\", or state \"The reagent valve will not response\". Error refers to the valve that selects which reagent will be pumped across the flow cell. These errors are less common with newer selector valves.\n\nThis error is usually caused by selector valve failure. Valve failure is much less frequent with v3 valves, and any instrument with earlier valves shouold have a v3 valve installed (PN 15040416S)\n\n1. Power cycle\n2. If no issues with re-initailization, run wash to ensure fluidics operating normally.\n3. If C_SW fails to initialize, or wash fails to complete successfully, Task Egr", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image18.png"}, {"Error message": "RFID Cannot Be Written Error on the MSQ", "Solution": "This error can appear during a run as the instrument checks RFID sensors. It is usually by a temporary communication failure, and will not stop a run or affect data quality.\n\n1. Allow run to continue\n2. Powercycle MSQ prior to next run", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image19.png"}, {"Error message": "RFID Not Recognized Error on the MSQ", "Solution": "MSQ Consumable are identified with RFID tags that contain the serial number and reagent version for the reagent cartridge, flow cell, and PR2 bottle. If these RFID tags cannot be read, C_SW will not allow run to be started. RFID tags that aren't recognized can be bypassed with a bypass code. In some cases, the RFID reader hardware requires adjustment or service.\n\n1. If first time or infrequently see error, get bypass code. If repeating issue, task Egr as may be faulty RFID reader.\n2. Log in to MyOriginFactor and click the more tab\n3. Expand My Tools and select MSQ Self-Service\n4. Expand the serial number of your instrument \n5. From the type of Override Code drop-down list, select RFID Override\n6. Click Get Code to generation the code.\n7. The bypass code is entered directly into C_SW and is valid for 7 days. Follow the prompts to enter the barcode and part number for the consumable. The location of this information on the reagent label is outlined below. The barcode number is highlighted in blue, the part number in yellow.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": "<img src=\"images/image20.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image21.png\">"}, {"Error message": "The process cannot access the file error on MSQ", "Solution": "This error can occur when a file is being scanned by virus software during the run, or when a communication issue occurs between the hardware end software. The run will often stop at the start of the next read. For example, if a virus scan is performed during Read 1 , the run will stop at the start of index Read 1.\n\nERROR: The process cannot access the file 'D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQTemp\\<RUN FOLDER>\\Recipe\\RunState.xml' because it is being used by another process.\n\n1. Review cycle logs to determine time of crash\n2. Review Windows log for virus scan and/ or GPO activity around time of crash\n3. Post run wash\n4. Powercycle MSQ.\n5. If instrument initializes without error and virus scan/ GPO activity were not found in logs, advise customer to set up next run\n6. If virus scan or GPO activity occured, send customer the following documents and request settings be updated bu internal IT Department before srtting up next run:\n* OriginFactor Proactive Tech Note\n* Configuring Virus Scanner Software on OriginFactor Sequencers\n* OriginFactor Security Best Practies Guide\n* MSQ System Site Prep Guide\n7. If error persisits during next run, task Egr as HDD may be required.", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image22.png"}, {"Error message": "How to re-route RTA copy files different output location on MSQ", "Solution": "This guide can be applied in cases where a server or network location goes down and leads to RTA being stuck\nwithout access to that output location. Usually, MSQ will accumulate raw data (e.g. TIFF and/or CIF files) and may\ncause D:\\ drive to be full and sequencing run automatically paused\n\nThe workaround for this is to either fix the problem in server/network or re-route RTA to save the run data to a\ndifferent output location, either locally in D:\\, external harddrive or different server.\n\n1. Terminate RTA.exe via Windows Task Manager\n2. Use Notepad modify lines following files, to include the new directory (e.g. D:\\)\n* <OutputFolder> in RunParameters.xml file\n3. <OutputFolder> in Data\\Intensities\\RTAConfiguration.xml\n4. Output file path in Line 3 in Config\\RTAStaart.bat (Leave quotation marks and do not introduce any extra characters)\n5. Restart RTA br running Config\\RTAStart.bat", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Sample Sheet will not Load into C_SW on MSQ", "Solution": "These errors are usually seen when C_SW cannot find the sample sheet for the run. They are often resolved easily by\nrenaming or moving the sample sheet.\n\n1. Check Sample sheet file:\nThe sample sheet must be located in the sample sheet folder and named so that C_SW can recognize it.\nFirst, make sure it is in the correct folder. The default location is D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Control\nSoftware\\SampleSheets, but this can be changed in the Folder Settings tab of Run Options, or specified for a\nparticular run. If the sample sheet is not in this folder, make a copy and place it in this folder.\nThe sample sheet should have a file name matching the barcode of the reagent cartridge. This allows C_SW\nto match the sample sheet to the run. The extension should be .csv.\nYou can also browse directly to a sample sheet if desired.\n2. Check Sample sheet format:\nThe sample sheet must be in the correct format. The easiest way to ensure correct formatting is to generate\nthe sample sheet in OriginFactor Experiment Manager. If IEM is not used, the sample sheet must be created as a\ncomma-separated text file according to the format described in the MSQ Sample Sheet Quick Reference\nGuide215. The file name is typically the same as the serial number from the reagent cartridge, although this\nis not required. The extension must be .csv.\nThere are several characters that should not be used in a sample sheet or title, including\n? ( ) [ ] / \\ = + < > : ; \" ' , * ^ | &\nThese characters can prevent the sample sheet from being loaded correctly.\n", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "SIPDOWN Errors on the MSQ", "Solution": "C_SW (C_SW) will show a SIPDOWN error if the reagent sippers are not functioning or canoot lower to pierce the foil on the reagent cartridge. This can be caused by physical obstruciton (if the reagent cartridge is not fully inserted or is damaged), a hardware problem with the sipper assembly, or a communicaiton error. This can simetimes be resolved easily, but sometimes indicates problem with the sipper assembly.  This error will occur before the run starts, when the sippers first lower, right after the customer hits the start button. This error can present in older versions of C_SW as an Object Reference error.\n\n1. Perfom post run wash\n2. Powercycle\n3. Verify no damage to reagents cartridge is fully thawed, and cartridge fully pushed back into instrument.\n4. If no indication of reagent cartridge damage, reset-up run with smae consumable\n5. If indication of reagent cartridge damage, please collect SN; Lot# and expiration date. Provide replacement cartridge if not expired\n\nIf reagent cartridge is pierced, it is typically worth attemptingt o start the run with the thawed cartridge. We can also check the C_SW logs to verify whether \"SIPDOWN\" error occured before or after the \"Start of run\":\n1. Check the C_SW logs to verify if \"SIPDOWN\" error occured before or after the \"Start of run\":\nIf \"SIPDOWN\" error is prior to \"Start of run\" consumable have not been marked as used and can be reused immediately.\nIf \"SIPDOWN\" error is after \"Start of run\" consumables have been marked as used and cannot reused.\n\n* If steps above do not clear error, assign work order to Egr to test the sipper function. The sipper motor, individual sippers, or the entire assembly may need to be replaced. ", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image23.png"}, {"Error message": "Stalled runs with BUBEN repeat on MSQ", "Solution": "Issue occurs when MSQ run stalls without an error in C_SW.\nSoftware freeze if run is paused\n\n1. Check cycle logs for repeating lines of \"@BUBEN2 C2 0 C1 0 R2 0 R1 0\"\n* Last cycle is very long\n* Before repeat occurred, run was progrssing normally.\n2. Check Windows logs around time in logs where @BUBEN2 started repeating dor errors.\n3. Confirm Anti-virus settings follow Security Best Practices\n4. Check for recently installed Windows updates.\n* Check for updates KB4056897 and KB4056894, If present, these updates are suspected cause of problem\n* Check for KB4512486. If present, report to Second Level Support. Update is under investigation, but has not been confirmed as problematic yet.\n* If any of Windows updates are present then unistall\n* If issue persists, assign work order to Egr dor HDD replacement.\n5. Chck Windows updates  settings\n* Navigate to Control Panel > Programs and Feature > View Installed Updates\n* Search for Services app\n* Double click Windows Update\n* Confirm startup type is disabled. If not, change setting\n6. Check instrument case history to see if issue has occurred previrously. Also recommend to check account case history to see if they have had stalls on other instruments at their site (which would suggest there may be an issue with anti-virus settings or GPO)", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": "<img src=\"images/image24.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image25.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image26.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image27.png\">"}, {"Error message": "How to fix TEC2SERVO unrecognize cahr error during C_SW initialization", "Solution": "C_SW fails to initialize due to error in Y motor:\n\nError caused by wrong regional settings in Windows\nRegional format must be set as English (United State) at all time.\n\n1. Select the Start button, and then select Control Panel\n2. Select Change date, time, or number formats\n3. The  Region dialog box appears\n4. On the Formats tab, select English (United states) from the dorp-down list. ", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Through-focus peak did not exceed SNR threshold Reeor at Cycle 1 on MSQ", "Solution": "The following errors may occur after the first cycle of imaging on the MSQ and indicate insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus. This can be due to too high of cluster density, too low of cluster density, or a complete failure to cluster.\n* Best focus ont found \n* Best focus is too near the edge of range\n* No usable signal found, it is possible clustering has failed\n* Through-foucs peak did ont exceed SNR threshold\n* Z Motor attempt to move outside soft limits\n* New in C_SW (C_SW) v4.0: ThroughFocusScan CoarseFocus failed to find focus, and there is no fallback position\n\nCycle 1 errors can result from library,  run step, instrument, and reagent issues\n\nCycle 1 errors indicate the instrument was unable to identify sufficient siganl  at cycle 1 and could not compatible the approriate focal point on the flow cell. Errors that occur after the first  cycle of imaging on the MSQ indicate there may be insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus.\n\nIf a focus error occurs later in the run (Such as in the first cycle of the index read or in the niddle of Read 1 or Read 4)  for futher information, search for Knowledge Base article(s): Troubleshooting best focus errors occuring mid-run on the MSQ, Troubleshooting Z motor erros occuring mid- run, and Troubleshooting No intensity for Index Read on MSQ.\n\nPossible instrument causes include:\n* Poor delivery of reagents involve in cluster generation or first base chemistry.\n* Flow cell temperature control issues.\n* Optical systems issues (rare)\n\nPossible library and reagent cause are:\n* Use of expired or improperly stored reagents\n* Library design and/ or quality/ quantificaiton issues.\n* Poor Read 1 primer hybridization due to library design issues\n* Use of incompatible preimers\n* Underclustered or overclustered libraries.\n* NaOH pH issue \n* Contamination of wassh tray\n\nTroubleshooting Steps:\nTo verify the instrument fluidics, temperature, and motion systems are performing as expected, first perform a SYS_Chk on the instrument as described in the MSQ System Guide:\n1. Perform the post run wash as prompted by the instument.\n2. Power cycle the instrument as described in the System Guide.\n3. Navigate to Manager instrument, then select SYS_Chk.\n4. Select all motion tests, primer reagent lines, and both thermal ramping and volume tests\n\nIf the SYS_Chk passes, the failure may be due to an issue with the library or reagents. To investigate the most common issues:\n1. Check reagent kits for expiration dates and proper storage.\n2. Make sure the library design is compatible to run on OriginFactor platforms.\n3. Chcek the quality and quantification of the library using OriginFactor-recommended methods.\n4. Make sure custom primers are compatible with the MSQ.\n5. Make sure cusotm primers are added to the correct cartridge wells (spiked into existing primer wells with no change to the smaple sheet, or added to custom primer wells with the sample sheet indicating that custom primers are being used).\n6. Confirm that a fresh dilution of NaOH was used and the pH is above 12.5.\n\nIf there are no apparent issues with library or reagents, repeat the run with a 20% PhiX control spike in. This will act as a positive control for clustring for the next run to determine  if the previous error was caused by an underlying library issue.", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image1.png"}, {"Error message": "ThroughFocusScan CoarseFocus failed to find focus, and there is no fallback positoin", "Solution": "New error messaging in C_SW 4.0, conditions that cause it are same as either \"Best Focus\" or \"SNR Threshold.\"\n\nThe following errors may occur after the first cycle of imaging on the MSQ and indicate insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus. This can be due to too high of cluster density, too low of cluster density, or a complete failure to cluster.\n* Best focus ont found \n* Best focus is too near the edge of range\n* No usable signal found, it is possible clustering has failed\n* Through-foucs peak did ont exceed SNR threshold\n* Z Motor attempt to move outside soft limits\n* New in C_SW (C_SW) v4.0: ThroughFocusScan CoarseFocus failed to find focus, and there is no fallback position\n\nCycle 1 errors can result from library,  run step, instrument, and reagent issues\n\nCycle 1 errors indicate the instrument was unable to identify sufficient siganl  at cycle 1 and could not compatible the approriate focal point on the flow cell. Errors that occur after the first  cycle of imaging on the MSQ indicate there may be insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus.\n\nIf a focus error occurs later in the run (Such as in the first cycle of the index read or in the niddle of Read 1 or Read 4)  for futher information, search for Knowledge Base article(s): Troubleshooting best focus errors occuring mid-run on the MSQ, Troubleshooting Z motor erros occuring mid- run, and Troubleshooting No intensity for Index Read on MSQ.\n\nPossible instrument causes include:\n* Poor delivery of reagents involve in cluster generation or first base chemistry.\n* Flow cell temperature control issues.\n* Optical systems issues (rare)\n\nPossible library and reagent cause are:\n* Use of expired or improperly stored reagents\n* Library design and/ or quality/ quantificaiton issues.\n* Poor Read 1 primer hybridization due to library design issues\n* Use of incompatible preimers\n* Underclustered or overclustered libraries.\n* NaOH pH issue \n* Contamination of wassh tray\n\nTroubleshooting Steps:\nTo verify the instrument fluidics, temperature, and motion systems are performing as expected, first perform a SYS_Chk on the instrument as described in the MSQ System Guide:\n1. Perform the post run wash as prompted by the instument.\n2. Power cycle the instrument as described in the System Guide.\n3. Navigate to Manager instrument, then select SYS_Chk.\n4. Select all motion tests, primer reagent lines, and both thermal ramping and volume tests\n\nIf the SYS_Chk passes, the failure may be due to an issue with the library or reagents. To investigate the most common issues:\n1. Check reagent kits for expiration dates and proper storage.\n2. Make sure the library design is compatible to run on OriginFactor platforms.\n3. Chcek the quality and quantification of the library using OriginFactor-recommended methods.\n4. Make sure custom primers are compatible with the MSQ.\n5. Make sure cusotm primers are added to the correct cartridge wells (spiked into existing primer wells with no change to the smaple sheet, or added to custom primer wells with the sample sheet indicating that custom primers are being used).\n6. Confirm that a fresh dilution of NaOH was used and the pH is above 12.5.\n\nIf there are no apparent issues with library or reagents, repeat the run with a 20% PhiX control spike in. This will act as a positive control for clustring for the next run to determine  if the previous error was caused by an underlying library issue.", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image1.png"}, {"Error message": "Tile Image Swapping on MSQ", "Solution": "Tile image swapping can occur on the MSQ during image capture.The C_SW (C_SW) is responsible\nfor capturing images (TIF files) and saving them to the hard drive. The MSQ uses a green LED to sequence G/T\nbases and a red LED to sequence A/C bases, so images are captured in the red and green channels. In some\ninstances, the red and green images can be swapped for a given tile. An investigation into the issue determined that\ntile image swapping occurs at a rate of 0.005%. This may cause a run to show an unexpectedly high number of lowfrequency\nvariant calls.\nThis issue is not specific to any one version of C_SW. Therefore, upgrading or downgrading the C_SW software will not\nresolve the issue. Also, replacing the hard drive does not resolve the issue. It is possible that the release of the Local\nRun Manager (LRM) software for the MSQ will resolve this issue.\nTo prevent this issue from affecting analysis (variant calling) results, the image swap needs to be identified (if it has\noccurred) and either the affected tile(s) or the affected BCL file(s) removed from the analysis. When PhiX is added to\na run, tile image swapping is easy to identify. When using a Micro flow cell, removing a tile from analysis will remove\n25% of the data. Instead of removing the affected tile, you can remove only the affected BCL file, which would\nremove just 1 cycle of data from 25% of the flow cell.\n\nHow To Identify Tile Image Swapping\nTile image swapping will manifest as a PhiX error rate spike, accompanied by a drop in quality scores for the\naffected tile in a single cycle of the run. Look for a tile image swap in SAV, by looking for an error rate spike (error\nrate ~50-70%) that’s isolated to a single and cycle.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": "<img src=\"images/image28.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image29.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image30.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image31.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image32.png\">\n<img src=\"images/image33.png\">"}, {"Error message": "How to requeue analysis of a run with MSQ Reporter", "Solution": "MSQ Reporter performs secondary analysis of data generated on the MSQ instrument. The run data can be reanalyzed\nmultiple times locally by requeueing analysis with MSQ Reporter. Some common reasons for requeueing\nanalysis include changing the analysis workflow or correcting index sequences, sample IDs, or sample names in the\nsample sheet. The instructions to edit the sample sheet correctly and requeue analysis with MSQ Reporter, either\nusing the web interface or from the run folder, are provided below. Always make sure that a sequencing run is not in\nprogress when requeuing analysis with MSQ Reporter.\n\nHow to edit the sample sheet\n1. Navigate to the MSQ Analysis run folder on the D drive. For example:\nD:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Analysis\\141007_M001_0016_000000000-AB8A8\n2. To edit the SampleSheet.csv file, open in it a text editor such as Notepad. If a spreadsheet editor is used,\nmake sure to save the sample sheet as a comma separated value (.csv) file. Make sure to maintain the format\nof the sample sheet.\n3. If a new sample sheet is created, keep a copy of the original sample sheet by renaming the SampleSheet.csv\nfile to SampleSheet_original.csv. Place the new sample sheet in the MSQ Analysis run folder and name it\nSampleSheet.csv.\n\nRequeue analysis of a run using the MSQ Reporter web interfacce\n1. To launch the MSQ Reporter web interface, open the Internet Explorer web browser and type http://\nlocalhost:8042220 in the address bar.\n2. From the MSQ Reporter web interface, select the Analyses tab on the top left.\n3. Locate the run from the list of available runs in the Analyses tab, click on the checkbox next to the run name, then select Requeue.\n\nDuring analysis, a status bar with elapsed time appears on the Analyses Info tab. If analysis needs to be stopped\nprior to completion, select the Stop analysis icon next to the status bar on the Analysis Info tab.\n\nRequeue without using the MSQ Repoter web interface\n1. If the run was sent to BaseSpace Sequence Hub, but has not been analyzed locally, the run will not be listed\nin the Analyses section of the MSQ Reporter web interface. In these situations, the analysis must be\nrequeued from the run folder. Once the analysis is requeued, the run will appear in the MSQ Reporter web interface. The following steps outline how to requeue analysis from the run folder.\n2. Navigate to the MSQ Analysis run folder on the D drive. For example:\nD:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Analysis\\141007_M001_0016_000000000-AB8A8\n3. Delete the file called queuedforanalysis.txt (or QueuedForAnalysis.txt) in the run folder. Deleting this file\nfrom the run folder triggers MSQ Reporter to start analysis. This file will reappear (as\nQueuedForAnalysis.txt) with current date and time stamp, indicating that MSQ Reporter has started analyzing the run.\n\nTo view the status of the analysis, open the Internet Explorer web browser and type http://localhost:8042221 in the\naddress bar to launch the MSQ Reporter web interface. Select the Analyses tab on the top left. The run that was\njust requeued will be at the bottom of the list. Select the run to see the status bar for the analysis.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Troubleshooting scratched or damaged flow cells on MSQ", "Solution": "All MSQ flow cells go through Quality Control before being shipped to customers.\nScratched flow cells may be used for sequencing if the scratches are minor or feather scratches as run performance\nis not typically impacted.\nIf damage is extensive (e.g. flow cell is cracked or there are multiple scratches), replace flow cell under consumable\nwarranty.\nTroubleshooting scratched flow cells:\nHave customer clean off flow cell with an ethanol wipe and dry with a lint-free lens cleaning tissue as\ndetailed in the MSQ System Guide223 .\nHave customer use flow cell for sequencing run and evaluate run data if customer is concerned about\nperformance.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Wash Notifications on the MSQ", "Solution": "\"It has been 7 or more days since the instrument fluidics were last used.\"\n\n1. Verify customer is selecting the DONE button at the end of the wash to log the wash\n2. Check washlog file located at D:\\\\OriginFactor\\Maintenance Logs folder\n3. Confirm date and time on the instrument is correct\n4. Power cycle the instrument\n5. If instrument still prompts for wash, close C_SW, move the WashStatus.xml(found in folder on D drive) to the desktop, and power cycle again. This will foece the software to crate a new WashStatus.xml file, which typically resolves notification issue.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Waste Bottle is Full Notification on the MSQ", "Solution": "Run will usually pause and give \"Waste bottle is full\" error.\n\n* Waste bottle may actually be full\n1. Empty waste bottle\n2. Put back on instrument\n3. Resume run\n* Error is given inaccurately\n1. Try cleaning the waste bottle sensor with an ethanol wipe and a lint-free wipe\nNote:  The sensor is the black bilb looking structure that can be seen at the topif the sipper into the waste bottle. To see it clearly, lift the sipper from the waste bottle, remove the bottle and you should be able to see the sensor\n2. Wipe down the sensor and resume run\n3. If error persists after cleaning sensor, power cycle\n4. If error persists after power cycle, task Egr", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Washes Taking Extended Time to Complete on MSQ", "Solution": "If any MSQ wash is taking too long to complete, it is possible the MSQ has had a communication error and is not proceeding with the wash as planned\n\n1. Confirm what wash intended and how long ago it was started. Verify time in wash is longer than what is expected for the type of wash\n* Quick wash: 20~30 min\n* Manual or Maintenance wash: 90 min\n* Stanby wash: 2 hr\n2. Power cycle\nor\n1. If control software is responsive, exit the wash and shutdown the MSQ\n2. If control software is not responsive, open the task manager to end the task for MSQ control\n\n* Shutdown MSQ through windows, and toggle power switch at back of instrument to off position. Leave powered down for full minute.\n* Power back up using switch on back, wait for C_SW to finish initializing\n* Repeat wash that was in progress and monitor for time to complete", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Y Motor Errors on MSQ", "Solution": "Y motor errors usually indicate communication problems with the stage or problem with stage hardware.\nError: Y Motor: Closed-loop movoe cannot reach target position: Start = 75.4150390625 mm, Target = 75.40472 mm, Distance = -0.0103190625000025 mm, Stopped at 74.42236328125 mm, ExceptionMessage = The FPGA reported an error while executing command \"YMVTO 154429\"; error message: \"Error: too many steps needed\"\nError: Timeout of 60.00 seconds exceeded while waiting for FPGA command \"YMVTILE 1327\" to complete\n\n1. Power cycle MSQ\n2. If no issues with re-initailization, repeat Y stage test 5x Instrumentation_MSQ_SYS_Chk Instruction\n3. If all Y stage tests pass continue with normal sequencing", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": "<img src=\"images/image36.png>\n<img src=\"images/image37.png>"}, {"Error message": "Z Motor attempt to move outsidesoft limits Error at Cycle 1 on MSQ", "Solution": "The following errors may occur after the first cycle of imaging on the MSQ and indicate insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus. This can be due to too high of cluster density, too low of cluster density, or a complete failure to cluster.\n* Best focus ont found \n* Best focus is too near the edge of range\n* No usable signal found, it is possible clustering has failed\n* Through-foucs peak did ont exceed SNR threshold\n* Z Motor attempt to move outside soft limits\n* New in C_SW (C_SW) v4.0: ThroughFocusScan CoarseFocus failed to find focus, and there is no fallback position\n\nCycle 1 errors can result from library,  run step, instrument, and reagent issues\n\nCycle 1 errors indicate the instrument was unable to identify sufficient siganl  at cycle 1 and could not compatible the approriate focal point on the flow cell. Errors that occur after the first  cycle of imaging on the MSQ indicate there may be insufficient cluster intensity for the instrument to find the best plane of focus.\n\nIf a focus error occurs later in the run (Such as in the first cycle of the index read or in the niddle of Read 1 or Read 4)  for futher information, search for Knowledge Base article(s): Troubleshooting best focus errors occuring mid-run on the MSQ, Troubleshooting Z motor erros occuring mid- run, and Troubleshooting No intensity for Index Read on MSQ.\n\nPossible instrument causes include:\n* Poor delivery of reagents involve in cluster generation or first base chemistry.\n* Flow cell temperature control issues.\n* Optical systems issues (rare)\n\nPossible library and reagent cause are:\n* Use of expired or improperly stored reagents\n* Library design and/ or quality/ quantificaiton issues.\n* Poor Read 1 primer hybridization due to library design issues\n* Use of incompatible preimers\n* Underclustered or overclustered libraries.\n* NaOH pH issue \n* Contamination of wassh tray\n\nTroubleshooting Steps:\nTo verify the instrument fluidics, temperature, and motion systems are performing as expected, first perform a SYS_Chk on the instrument as described in the MSQ System Guide:\n1. Perform the post run wash as prompted by the instument.\n2. Power cycle the instrument as described in the System Guide.\n3. Navigate to Manager instrument, then select SYS_Chk.\n4. Select all motion tests, primer reagent lines, and both thermal ramping and volume tests\n\nIf the SYS_Chk passes, the failure may be due to an issue with the library or reagents. To investigate the most common issues:\n1. Check reagent kits for expiration dates and proper storage.\n2. Make sure the library design is compatible to run on OriginFactor platforms.\n3. Chcek the quality and quantification of the library using OriginFactor-recommended methods.\n4. Make sure custom primers are compatible with the MSQ.\n5. Make sure cusotm primers are added to the correct cartridge wells (spiked into existing primer wells with no change to the smaple sheet, or added to custom primer wells with the sample sheet indicating that custom primers are being used).\n6. Confirm that a fresh dilution of NaOH was used and the pH is above 12.5.\n\nIf there are no apparent issues with library or reagents, repeat the run with a 20% PhiX control spike in. This will act as a positive control for clustring for the next run to determine  if the previous error was caused by an underlying library issue.", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image1.png"}, {"Error message": "Z motor errors occuring mid-run on the MSQ", "Solution": "Either instrument fluidics, debirs, smudges on flow cell, or library/overclustering issues can lead to a mid-run z motor error.\nError: While trying to find focus, the Zstage has attempted to move outside its acceptable range\n\n1. Review run data including thumbnail images to confirm run performance. If library issue is not suspected, troubleshoot instrument.\n* Check reagent kits for expiration dates and proper storage\n* Make sure the library design is compatible to run on OriginFactor platforms\n* Check the quality and quantificaiton of the library using OriginFactor-recommended methods\n* Make sure custom primers are compatible with the 65℃ annealing temperature for the MSQ.\n* Make sure custom primers are added to the correct cartridge wells (spiked in existing primer wells with no change to the sample sheet, or added to custom primer wells with the sample sheet indicating that custom primers are being used).\n2. To ensure that the instrument's fluidics, temperature and motion systems are performing as expected, first power cycle and perform a SYS_Chk on the instrument.\n3. If SYS_Chk passes, set up next run\n4. If Z motor error recurs in subsequent run, assign work order to Egr.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Z Motor the Zstage amp op-amp might not be wired correctly on MSQ", "Solution": "Possible causes: common issue, Z seating cables or Z stage issues.\nError can occur at cycle 1 or mid-run\nERROR: Z Motor: The Z stagge/amp/Op-amp might not be weird correctly: Setting DAC to 2.000 V and 8.000 V caused SGS monitor voltage to read 8.830 V and 8.850 V, which is not enough change. (System.Exception)\n* Unable to home Z motor\n\n1. Post eun wash\n2. Powercycle MSQ\n3. Perform Z stage SYS_Chk 5 times\n4. If error persists, instrument fails to initialize, or one of the Z stage fails, task Egr\n5. If instrument initailizes without error, advise customer to set up next run\n6. If next eun fails with the same error, task Egr", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Z Motor Positive soft limit too nonlinear at innermost test point on the MSQ", "Solution": "\"Z Motor: Positive soft limit too nonlinear even at innermost test point: Target = -20.000 um, actual = -16.287 um, error= 3.713 um, tolerance = 0.100 um (System.Exception)\"\nUsually occurs at cycle 1, after power cycle, or start of wash\n\n1. Power cycle\n2. If C_SW initializes successfully - continue with SYS_Chk (motion test - Z stage test repeat 5X)\n* If SYS_Chk passes - continue with nexxt seqeuncing run\n* If SYS_Chk does not pass the Z stage - task Egr\n3. If C_SW fails to initialize - Task Egr", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Cannot process request because the process has exited error on MSQ", "Solution": "Initialization error message:\nC_SW could not be started. Contact OriginFactor Technical Support.\nCannot process request because the process (error ID) has exited\n\n1. Power cycle\n2. Initialize C_SW (C_SW)\n3. If issue persists,  Egr re-install C_SW", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "MSQOverride.cfg Errors on MSQ", "Solution": "Error message 'C:\\MSQ Config\\MSQOverride.cfg'', section '[Focus Params]' defines 'TiltUntltFocusCenterZ = -- 0.156016', which is an invalid float\n\nAt the start of a run the MSQ reference the MSQOverride.cfg file to determine calibration location. This file provide information specific for the system. During preventative maintenance or service visits, Egr may take minor updates to this file. If a syntax error is intriduced, the MSQ may fail to accurately parse the MSQOverride.cfg and stop the next run.\n\n1. Confirm via instrument history or with customer if a recent service visit has been completed\n2. Close C_SW and Collect MSQOverride.cfg from C:\\MSQ Config\\MSQOverride.cfg\n3. Review the file with Egr to identify any syntax errors and correct\n4. Replace the corrected file into C:\\MSQ Config folder\n5. Power cycle the MSQ", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image37.png"}, {"Error message": "Troubleshooting Free Disk Space errors during Pre-run Checks on MSQ", "Solution": "If dissk space is low, message appears indicating how much disk space is required.\n\nUse the Manage Files feature to clear the required space from the instrument computer\n\nFiles can be deleted drom the MSQ Temp, MSQ Analysis, and MSQ Output folders\n\nThe recycle bin must be emptied before the Pre-Run checks can be performed again", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Troubleshooting Network Connection Active errors during Pre-run Check on MSQ", "Solution": "Make sure that the network cable is pluggeed into the instrument\nIf the network connection is not restored, select Reboot on the Manage Instrument screen to re boot the software\nIf the connection is still not restored, select Shut Down on the Manage Instrument screen, and then turn off the instrument using the power switcj. Wait at least 60 seconds, and then turn on the instrument and start the software", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Troubleshooting Primary Analysis Ready errors during Pre-run Checks on MSQ", "Solution": "This error occurs when primary analysis from the previous run is not complete. The default time to allow primary analysis to complete is one hour, and a countdown appears on the screen. The options are to wait one hour or select Terminate Analysis. Selecting Terminate Analysis results in secondary analysis stopping for any incomplete cycles.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "The instrument is not correctly configured to communicate with BaseSpace error on MSQ", "Solution": "Issue: The customer is unable to login to BaseSpace when setting up their run\n\nEeeor message: The instrument is not correctly configured to communicate with BaseSpace. Please contact technical support\n\n1. Check the BaseSpace Broker logs (D:\\OriginFactor\\basespace broker) for the error: \"Unable to locate: C:\\Include_Override.cfg or C:\\MSQOverride.cfg\"\n1. This error indicates that the file MSQOverride.cfg is missing from C:\n2. There are supposed to be 2 files named MSQOverride.cfg on the MSQ PC with different content\n3. C:\\MSQOverride.cfg contains just 1 line of tect that points to C:\\MSQConfig\\MSQOverride.cfg\n* If C:\\MSQOverride.cfg is not present, then the pointer file is missing\n1. Create a text filel named C:\\MSQOverride.txtand add the text: ;#include\"C:\\MSQ Config\\MSQOverride.cfg\"\n2. Change the text file to a .cfg file\n3.  Restarat BaseSpace Broker (Task Manager > Services > OriginFactor BaseSpace Broker)\n1. If both copies of MSQOverride.cfg are identical, then the pointer file is missing\n1. Rename the incorrect file to MSQOverride.cfg.bak\n2. Create a text file named C:\\MSQOverride.txt and add the text: ;#include \"C:\\MSQ Config\\MSQOverride.cfg\"\n3. Change the text file to a .cfg file\n4. Restart BaseSpace Broker (Task manager > Servies > OriginFactor BaseSpace Broker)", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Unsuccessfully attempted to launch module type error wuth LRM V3 on MSQ", "Solution": "Issue with LRM V3: Unable to start run under Sample Sheet mode. Error when importing sample sheet previously generated in LRM.\n* Error message: 'Unsuccessfully attempted to launch module type GenerateFastQWorkflow'\n* Error will likely impact any/ all the v3 LRM Module: includes GenerateDASTQ3.0.1, LibraryQC v2.1.0, Resequencing v3.0.1, DNA Amplicon v3.0.0 and other modules\n\nCause of issue\n* When worker process and dll is still in use while user try to install a newer version of the module.\n\nResolution:\n* Uninstall the module and then re-install it. Then, try to import the sample sheet again via C_SW", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Windows 10 MSQ LRM error caused by incompatible sample sheet generated by IEM", "Solution": "MSQ with Windows 10 OS is running C_SW (C_SW) v4 with Local Run Manager (LRM) v3.\nBecause OriginFactor Experiment Manager (IEM) and LRM v3 format information differently, IEM sample sheets are not compatible with LRM v3 and CANNOT be converted to LRM v3 sample sheets.\n\nWhe customers impor an IEM sample sheet into LRmv3 during new run set up, it will trigger an error message \"a valid index kit must be provided for the selected library prep kit\".\n\nPlease recommend that the customer download the Template sample sheet from the desired LRM module, manually populate,and upload back into the module while setting up a new run in LRMv3. Customer can also directly input run information into LRMv3 mofule new run set up without using the import Sample Sheet function.\n\nIEM generated sample sheets are also NOT compatible with C_SW (C_SW) v4 \"Sample Sheet\" mode Run Setup Option. Errors will occur if customers use an IEM sample sheet to try to set up a new run within C_SW v4. Properly formatted sample sheets can be created within LRMv3, or via templates downloaded directly from LRM or from the OriginFactor Support website. Instruction on how to find correct sample sheet found", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": "<img src=\"images/image39.png>\n<img src=\"images/image38.png>"}, {"Error message": "Green LED: Failed polling LED status error on MSQ (C_SW v4.0.0)", "Solution": "In C_SW v4.0.0, some runs have a notification message: GreenLED: Failed polling LED status. The message typically does not stop the run, and a comminication issue is suspected\n\n1. Power cycle MSQ after run completes\n2. If no issues with re-initailization, monitor next run.", "image": "圖片", "Unnamed: 3": "images/image40/png"}, {"Error message": "C_SW (C_SW) v4 stalling during initialization", "Solution": "This issue has been observed when power cycling MSQ to resolve upload issues to Beasespace and a network location. Upload issues are Universal Copy Service (UCS) related.\n\nPhenotype :\nAfter power cycling UCS will resume file upload and C_SW v4 stalls during initialization. C_SW does not fail to initialize and does not show an error\nSuspected cause: Old .json files are in state 'Active'\n\n1. Close C_SW in Task Manager \n2. Open Services app as administrator (right click on Services app).\n3. Stop UCS\n4. Navigate to C:\\ProgramData\\OriginFactor\\UniversalCopyService\\Runs\n5. Open .json files with Notepad and change and change run state to 'Done' OR remove old .json files from Runs folder.\n6. Start UCS in Services app and open C_SW", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "Consecutive camera failure limit has been exceeded for this run error on C_SW (C_SW) v4.0 error on MSQ", "Solution": "The \"Consecutive camera failure limt has been exceeded for this run error on C_SW (C_SW) v4.0\" \nError can result from any hardware involved with the execution of the tile scan, thus any hardware not related to fluidics.\n\nError message in C_SW v4.0:\n\"Consecutive camera failure limit has been exceeed for this run. The eun is being aborted. Contact Technical Support\"\n\nTo troubleshoot, review the run cycle logs (D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Temp\\<Run_Folder>\\Logs) to find error that stopped run. Troubleshoot following guidance bassed on error.\n\nLogs can be parse for the following statement:\nFor camera related exceptions, looks for the following statement:\n\"Failed to perform unknown Camera parallel functions due to non camera issue, retry #{0},Max Retries: {1}.Exceptioin Message{2}\"\n\nFor non-camera related exceptions, look for the following statement:\n\"Failed to perform unknown Camera parellel fuctions due to non camera issue, retry #{0}, Max Retries: {1}.Exception Message {2}\" \n\nIf limited information is available on error found in the cycle logs, contact second Level support dor futher guidance.\n\nExample scenario:\nCustomer received error in C_SW v4: \"Consecutive camera failure limit has been exceeded for this run. The\nrun is being aborted. Contact Technical Support.\"\nError found in cycle logs: \"The FPGA reported an error while executing command \"FOCMRRFOC\" error\nmessage: \"Focus Mirror sensor not found.\"\nGuidance for Focus Mirror Error on MSQ(see page 99) should be followed for troubleshooting", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "How to Plot OfEgrts on the MSQ ", "Solution": "MSQ offstes can plotted when an image registration issue or stage movement issue is suspected. Plot shows how far RTA has to optically shift image to align it to the template map.\n\nHow to plot ofEgrts:\n1. Collect ofEgrt files from the instrument D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Temp\\<Run_Folder>\\Data\\Intensties\\OfEgrt.txt\n2. Download ofEgrts template file: MSQ---\n3.  Paste the following faata drom the ofEgrt.txt file into the template:\n* Filter by 1 Lane, 1 Tile, 1 Surface\n* All cycles\n* Channel 0 (is the master reference)\n4. Plot x and y ofEgrt vs cycle\nWhat to expect:\n* +/-150 pixels is the upper limit of correction\n* Slow changes up to +/- 50 pixels can be normal\n* Jagged plots and large shifts outside of +/- 50 can indicate an issue", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": "<img src=\"images/image41.png>\n<img src=\"images/image42.png\">"}, {"Error message": "Making a Tile from RTA on the MSQ", "Solution": "If a tile does not have any clusters passing filter, then no data will be extractrd from that tile. This can cause RTA to stop converting intensity flies (cifs) to base calls (bcls) after read 1. In order ro get RTA to move onto the next read for processing, we will need to mask the tiles that are not generating any data. Basicall, we're hiding specific tiles from RTA so it won't even know anything is missing\n1. First, identify what tiles you need to mask (the dlow cell charrt inSAV is ouyr friend for this!)\n* Can also look in D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Temp\\<Run ID>\\Processed\\L001\\ and chcek for any tiles that have not processed the .cif files\n* Tile naming convertion is Lane_Surface/Swath/Tile\n* MSQ v2 chemistry has two surface (top and bottom), one swath, and 28 tiles (14 per surface)\n* MSQ v3 chemistry has two surface (top and bottom) , one swath, and 38 tiles (19 per surface)\n2. Terminate RTA open Task Manager, select 'RTA.exe' under the processes tab, and select \"End Process\"\n3. Go to Processed folder in local MSQ Temp run folder (D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQTemp\\<run folder>\\Processed), you'll see a folder per lane, i.e. L001 for lane 1\n4. Sort the files by clicking the type column of the window\n5. Find the .locs (location) file for the tile you want to mask, and rename it by adding \".bak\" at the end of the file name, i.e. s_1_2216.locs.bak\n6. Do this for all tile you want to mask\n7. Navvigate to D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQTemp\\<Run Folder>\\Data\\Intensities\\Base Calls, and open Config.xml in Notepad, and then delete the line with the tile that need to be masked\n* For example, delete the line that says <Tile>2116<Tile> to remove Tile 2116\n8. Navigate to D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQTemp\\<Run Folder>\\Data\\Intensities\\ and open the Config.xml file (this is a different file that is uesd by MSQ Reporter!) and delete the line with the Tile that need to be masked\n9. Finally, manually launch RTA by double clicking RTAstart.bat filefound D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Temp\\<run folder>\\Config adn watch the magic happen on the Tile Status tab of large RTA window", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}, {"Error message": "How to Stop and Restart RTA on MSQ", "Solution": "RTA(Real-Time Analysis) is an intergrated software that anlyzes flow cell images and calculates metrics during a eun. You may need to manually stop and restart RTA if it is stalled or if the network path is down.\n\nTo restart RTA on the MSQ:\n1. To condirm that RTA has not completed, verify that there is no RTAComplete.txt file present in the run folder (D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Temp\\<run folder>)\n2. Select the Windows start button (bottom left of the computer screen), and search for Task Manager.\n* Alternatively, press Ctrl+Alt+Delete on the keyboard to open Task Manager\n3. In Task Manger, select the Processes tab, right-click on RTA.exe, and select End Process.\n4. To restart RTA, double-click the RTAstart.bat file, located in D:\\OriginFactor\\MSQ Temp\\<run folder>\\Config.\n5. Confirm that RTA.exe is present in the Task Manager Processes tab. Note: A small black command prompt window indicates that RTA is running. You can minimize this window.", "image": NaN, "Unnamed: 3": NaN}];